section.p:
If \theta is an acute angle in a right triangle, the sine, cosine and tangent of  are given by the following ratios:


    \sin \theta \amp = \frac{\text{length of side opposite }\theta}{\text{length of hypotenuse}}
    \cos \theta \amp = \frac{\text{length of side adjecent }\theta}{\text{length of hypotenuse}}
    \tan \theta \amp = \frac{\text{length of side opposite }\theta}{\text{length of side adjacent }\theta}


  These ratios enable us to determine the measures of all parts of a right triangle if we know the measure of at least three parts including the right angle.  Recall from your study of geometry that at least one of the known parts must be the measure of a side, since three angles do not determine a unique triangle. The process of determining the measures of all unknown angles and sides is called solving a triangle.

solution.p:
shows a sketch of the given information.  The angle of elevation is \angle CAD  and BC represents the distance traveled by the plane during the minute it was observed.


    Diagram for 



   If we find the distance the plane travels in one minute, we can convert feet per minute to miles per hour to obtain the speed of the plane.  Since \angle BAC  and \angle CAD  are complementary angles, we know that  \angle BAC=90^\circ - 15^\circ =75^\circ.  Using right triangle ABC and the tangent ratio, we can now solve for side BC as follows:


    \tan \angle BAC   \amp = \frac{BC}{AB}
    \tan 75^\circ BAC \amp = \frac{BC}{2500 \text{ ft.}}
    BC                \amp = (2500 \text{ ft.})\tan 75^\circ=9330 \text{ ft.}


   The plane travels about 9330 feet in one minute.  We can convert to miles per hour as follows:
   \frac{9330 \text{ ft.}}{1 \text{ min}}=\frac{9330 \text{ ft.}}{1 \text{ min}} \cdot \frac{60 \text{ min}}{1 \text{ hr}}=\frac{1 \text{ mile}}{5280 \text{ ft.}}=106 \text{ mph}.

We know the length of only one side, so we need to use the Law of Sines rather than the Law of Cosines to find the length of side CD.


    \frac{\sin 20^\circ}{CD} \amp =\frac{\sin 130^\circ}{15}
    CD                       \amp =\frac{15}{\sin 130^\circ}\cdot \sin 20^\circ
                             \amp =6.7\text{ miles}


   Similarly, we can find the length of side PC.


    \frac{\sin 30^\circ}{PC} \amp =\frac{\sin 130^\circ}{15}
    PC                       \amp =\frac{15}{\sin 130^\circ}\cdot \sin 30^\circ
                             \amp =9.8\text{ miles}


   Adding the lengths of  sides PC and CD, we conclude that they traveled approximately 16.5 miles to reach their destination.

To use the Law of Sines to find the length of side BC, we first need the measure of \angle DAC in right triangle ACD.  Since the length of AC and DC are known, we can use the tangent relationship.


     \tan \left( \angle DAC \right) \amp =\frac{101}{503}
     \angle DAC                     \amp =11.35^\circ


   The measure of \angle BAC =20^\circ + \text{ measure of } \angle DAC.  Therefore, the measure of \angle BAC =31.35^\circ, and the measure of \angle ABC =101.65^\circ.  Using triangle ABC and the Law of Sines,


     \frac{BC}{\sin 31.35^\circ} \amp =\frac{503 \text{ cm}}{\sin 101.65^\circ}
     BC                          \amp =267.2 \text{ cm.}


   In the solution above, the angles were measured to the nearest hundredth of a degree.  If the angles had been rounded to the nearest degree, the Law of Sines would produce a different result:


     \frac{BC}{\sin 31^\circ} \amp =\frac{503 \text{ cm}}{\sin 102^\circ}
     BC                       \amp =264.9 \text{ cm.}


   As you would expect, the angle measures used in first solution produce a more accurate answer for the length of BC.  In solving problems, it is best to hold more digits in the intermediate steps and to round in the final answer.

When using technology, a good strategy is to solve the equation(s) using algebra without making any numerical substitutions.  Using this method in Example 6 leads to the following steps:


     \tan \left(\angle DAC \right) \amp =\frac{101}{503}
     \angle DAC                    \amp =\tan^{-1} \left(\frac{101}{503} \right)


   Substituting in the Law of Sines,


    \frac{BC}{\sin 20^\circ+\tan^{-1} \left(\frac{101}{503} \right)} \amp =\frac{503}{\sin \left(180^\circ-47^\circ-20^\circ \right)-\tan^{-1} \left(\frac{101}{503} \right)}
    BC \amp =267.2 \text{ cm}


   Equation  is exactly true with no estimations of any values. When the value of BC is calculated, rounding can be done knowing the value is based on the accuracy in the original measurements.
